        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>I had reason to take the greater paines in reading the first decad of Liuie, bie meanes of mie dailie &amp; almost howerlie conference 
                        with M. Thomas Preston a fine discourser, &amp; the Queenes onlie pensionar scholler: when in owre chambers in Trinitie hall with mutch delight, 
                        &amp; more proffit wee read togither in Italian, which the Florentine secretarie writeth with an elegant &amp; sweet grace: 
                        Discorsi di Niccolo Machiauelli, sopra la prima deca di Tito Liuio. which politique discourses wee thorowghly redd-ouer: 
                        with diligent &amp; curious observations of the notable actions of the Romans, accomplished at home, &amp; abrode, 
                        bie publique, &amp; priuate counsell: at home in the first book: abrode in the 2: both bie publique counsell: 
                        at home &amp; aborode bie priuate counsell in the 3. Which method in Machiauels discourses wee soone discouered: 
                        &amp; the more casely distinguished his politique positions. Supposing his councels of state, uery fitt to be annexed to owr principall councels, 
                        &amp; souerain decisions in Lawe. Wee then had studied Hotomans Lawe–book Qua[e]stionum illustrium. 
                        And were in hand with Marantas ten disputations Qua[e]stionum legalium.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Thomas Preston"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Machiavelli"/>
                    <person name="Francois Hotman"/>
